T1  - An Analysis of Individual Decision Making Behavior Using a Laboratory Setting
AU  - Cecil, Earl A.
AU  - Lundgren, Earl F.
Y1  - 1975/09/01
PY  - 1975
DA  - 1975/09/01
N1  - doi: 10.5465/255688
DO  - 10.5465/255688
T2  - Academy of Management Journal
JF  - Academy of Management Journal
JO  - AMJ
SP  - 600
EP  - 604
VL  - 18
IS  - 3
PB  - Academy of Management
N2  - This article presents an analysis of individual decision making behavior using a laboratory setting. The author states that one's aspiration level is determined by one's history of successes and failures as well as current cues to the probability of future successes. In 1966 researcher P. Soelberg added the confirmation phase to the process of decision making. Studying the job selection of graduate students, Soelberg found that subjects first developed an active list of acceptable alternatives, only stopping their search when they were able to settle on a satisfactory alternative. During the following confirmation phase, the comparison among alternatives was reduced to two, the choice candidate and a confirmation candidate. From these two alternatives, a final selection is typically made.
AB  - This article presents an analysis of individual decision making behavior using a laboratory setting. The author states that one's aspiration level is determined by one's history of successes and failures as well as current cues to the probability of future successes. In 1966 researcher P. Soelberg added the confirmation phase to the process of decision making. Studying the job selection of graduate students, Soelberg found that subjects first developed an active list of acceptable alternatives, only stopping their search when they were able to settle on a satisfactory alternative. During the following confirmation phase, the comparison among alternatives was reduced to two, the choice candidate and a confirmation candidate. From these two alternatives, a final selection is typically made.
SN  - 0001-4273
M3  - doi: 10.5465/255688
UR  - https://doi.org/10.5465/255688
Y2  - 2026/04/24
