T1  - Efficiency of Workers on the Four-Day Workweek
AU  - Calvasina, Eugene J.
AU  - Boxx, W. Randy
Y1  - 1975/09/01
PY  - 1975
DA  - 1975/09/01
N1  - doi: 10.5465/255689
DO  - 10.5465/255689
T2  - Academy of Management Journal
JF  - Academy of Management Journal
JO  - AMJ
SP  - 604
EP  - 610
VL  - 18
IS  - 3
PB  - Academy of Management
N2  - This article presents information on a study analyzing the efficiency of workers within a a four-day workweek. There has been favorable reaction to the concept of a four-day workweek schedule, leading to increased employee morale and productivity as well as reduced turnover and absenteeism. The author expresses concern over opinion data not reflecting valid results of the effects of the four-day workweek on worker efficiency. According to a study conducted by researcher Franklin Poper on the relationship of reduced hours and productivity, the results of direct studies differ significantly from those based on indirect studies. In 427 of the 936 indirect studies reviewed, respondents reported that productivity either declined or remained unchanged, compared to only 14 of 160 direct studies reporting similar results.
AB  - This article presents information on a study analyzing the efficiency of workers within a a four-day workweek. There has been favorable reaction to the concept of a four-day workweek schedule, leading to increased employee morale and productivity as well as reduced turnover and absenteeism. The author expresses concern over opinion data not reflecting valid results of the effects of the four-day workweek on worker efficiency. According to a study conducted by researcher Franklin Poper on the relationship of reduced hours and productivity, the results of direct studies differ significantly from those based on indirect studies. In 427 of the 936 indirect studies reviewed, respondents reported that productivity either declined or remained unchanged, compared to only 14 of 160 direct studies reporting similar results.
SN  - 0001-4273
M3  - doi: 10.5465/255689
UR  - https://doi.org/10.5465/255689
Y2  - 2026/04/24
